My quick BOE calculations show about 31 supernovas per second:

100 billion galaxies in the observable universe
1 supernova per 100 years per galaxy
= 1 billion supernovas per year = 31.7 per second.

Checking your source estimates, and using 2 trillion galaxies and 2 supernovas per 100 years per galaxy, we multiply that 40 to get about 1200 SNs per second, or 300 per .25 sec eye blink! Well, what do you know. Impressive either way.

EDIT: I now think that 2 SNs per 100 years per galaxy is too high, since 80% of galaxies are dwarfs that would not have such a high rate.

2,000 years ago, God became a human being, Jesus of Nazareth, who suffered and died on the cross for our sins and rose from the dead on the third day, defeating death. The punishment that we deserve for breaking God's law, Jesus took in our place. He paid the fine that we could never pay so that God can legally set us free by forgiving our sins. He is just, by punishing evil through Jesusâ€™ death on the cross, while being rich in mercy towards us.

What you have to do is repent, or turn toward God, and believe in Jesus Christ. Don't trust your own goodness, because, as Jesus said, â€œNo one is good â€” except God aloneâ€ (Mark 10:18). The moment you do that, God will forgive every sin you have ever committed and grant you eternal life, and He will give you a new heart with new desires, so that you will love to do what is right.
